After this workshop we were invited to join a research group that was bidding for new research on the cultural heritage of Europe's minor waterways. This was successful (AHRC EUWATHER)</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2015</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The findings have been used as part of a pilot approach to gathering and interpreting the oral histories of displaced people newly arrived in the UK. Out approach was used because it was important to provide a space in which peopel could tell, retell and relive their stories in ways that are not offered by more conventional approaches to oral history research</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2013</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>46E772AA-289B-45D6-8799-5511D8955784</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Cultural,Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education,Government, Democracy and Justice,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Through a series of co-created and facilitated workshops and training programmes, this project has brought facilitation practice into conversation with academic research methods to create a co-designed multi-method model for organising the generation of data about personal and community histories and associations. This model, termed the Community Stories Spiral (CSS), represents a 'shared space' that has been developed through a collaborative effort involving sharing and transfer of knowledge and skills. The CSS has since been used to examine a range of community-based issues, in the process challenging conventional academic constructions of community as largely isolated and static.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The findings have been used by European researchers looking at the ways in which people living near small waterways make a sense of place out of those waterways. The findings have also been used to help understand the oral histories of displaced people newly arrived in the UK. In both cases it was important that the research method did not pre-judge or pre-figure what or who was important in terms of the stories that were told.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>BFBD089F-E288-4635-ACF3-2BCA89E3B337</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Education,Government, Democracy and Justice,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>This is a new conceptual frame within which to conduct oral and community histories research</gtr:description><gtr:id>D3C6E3B8-81E4-4FA0-81CD-0C804F56F0F9</gtr:id><gtr:impact>None yet</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Collaborative Stories Spiral</gtr:title><gtr:type>Improvements to research infrastructure</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2015</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/940C81FE-C5FB-404E-8B9C-E43A8B114591"><gtr:id>940C81FE-C5FB-404E-8B9C-E43A8B114591</gtr:id><gtr:title>Co-designing non-hierarchical community arts research: the collaborative stories spiral</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Qualitative Research Journal</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/d5cffbe522a6953ac96ad3eb29784